docs.lead_paragraph: IT has always been the custom of the historical novelist to introduce imaginary personages, upon whom he depends for his love-story. The reader has thus the pleasing element of uncertainty, which incalculably heightens the interest of romance. The writer of the biographical novel has no such resource; if he departs from fact we feel defrauded; if he adheres to it we are likely to be bored.

docs.snippet: THE "waif" of Miss Broughton's story is no shivering and starving urchin of the streets, but a beautifully gowned, bewitching girl of nearly eighteen Summers -- a waif none the less, in that nothing save grudging hospitalities stand between her an...
docs.lead_paragraph: THE "waif" of Miss Broughton's story is no shivering and starving urchin of the streets, but a beautifully gowned, bewitching girl of nearly eighteen Summers -- a waif none the less, in that nothing save grudging hospitalities stand between her and homeless destitution. She has an inheritance of "drink on both sides, immorality on both sides, selfishness on both sides, extravagance and folly on both sides," as summed up by a stern benefactress.

docs.lead_paragraph: PRAIRIE DU CHIEN, Wis., Nov. 12. -- Practically every person in Crawford County spent the larger part of the day seeking for Agnes Pfeifer, the young heiress who was mysteriously abducted from school at noon on Thursday. The hunt was all in vain. The police traced the girl to two miles from the schoolhouse where the abduction took place, but the combined efforts of the police and county people brought no further results.

docs.lead_paragraph: NEW BRUNSWICK, Nov. 12. -- A tribute from Jeremiah Grundelis, an Italian sculptor, to the memory of his four-year-old son Bruno, was unveiled last week in St. Francis's Cemetery, at Methuchen. The figure of an angel, mounted on a pedestal, bearing in its arms the form of a child, the counterpart of the little boy, makes a sculpture eight feet high. The boy died last June, while his parents were living in Methuchen.

docs.lead_paragraph: NEWPORT NEWS, Nov. 14. -- Secretary William H. Taft of the War Department reached Hampton Roads to-day aboard the cruiser Columbia after a trip of investigation to the Panama Canal zone. The Columbia arrived in the Roads at 9 o'clock this morning, but because of a heavy snowstorm the Secretary decided to remain aboard all day. He left the Columbia on the ship's cutter about 7 o'clock this evening and boarded a steamboat for Washington.

docs.lead_paragraph: GLEN RIDGE, N.J., Nov. 19. -- A Maltese cat, wearing Princeton colors about its neck, strayed from its home in Washington Street yesterday afternoon. At the corner of Midland Avenue a bulldog barred the road. The cat tackled, and for a time seemed to be making ground. When the bulldog rallied the cat hurdled, landing about ten feet up a telegraph pole, and immediately afterward making a touchdown at the top of the pole.

docs.lead_paragraph: MOUNT VERNON, N.Y., Nov. 21. -- The meeting of the Board of Aldermen here to-night bordered on a riot. During the proceedings Mayor Brush called on the police to arrest Alderman Clark, one of two Republican leaders of the board. Roundsman Riley and Patrolman Gilroy made their way to Clark, while the crowd, which was in sympathy with the Mayor, yelled approval, but Clark subsided before the policemen reached him.

docs.lead_paragraph: DULUTH, Nov. 29. -- Estimates of the losses in yesterday's storm on the great lakes are 40 deaths and a money loss of upward of $2,000,000. Of this loss the six vessels wrecked almost within sight of Superior foot up a total of at least $1,500,000. The loss of life in lake disasters this year will thus be brought to over 125.

docs.lead_paragraph: ST. PETERSBURG, Nov. 29. -- Father Gapon is here in hiding. In an interview to-day he expressed the opinion that the revolutionary leaders were making the tactical mistake which he made before Jan. 22 of preaching an armed rebellion, a democratic republic, and an immediate eight-hour day. He said that his residence abroad had opened his eyes. Time was necessary to realize the Socialistic ideals.
